.TH _PRINTF 3 "January 2026" "Holberton School" "Library Functions Manual"
.SH NAME
_printf \- print formatted output to standard output
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B #include "main.h"
.PP
.BI "int _printf(const char *" format ", ...);"
.SH DESCRIPTION
The
.B _printf()
function writes formatted output to the standard output stream (stdout).
It behaves like the standard
.BR printf (3)
in a simplified way.

The
.I format
string is a sequence of ordinary characters and conversion directives.
Ordinary characters are printed as they appear.
A conversion directive starts with the character
.B %
and is followed by a conversion specifier.

This implementation does not support flags, field width, precision, or length modifiers.

.SH CONVERSION SPECIFIERS
.TP
.B %c
Print a single character.
.TP
.B %s
Print a string. If the string is NULL, it prints
.BR "(null)" .
.TP
.B %d
Print a signed decimal integer.
.TP
.B %i
Print a signed decimal integer (same behavior as
.BR %d ).
.TP
.B %%
Print a literal percent sign.

Any other specifier after
.B %
is printed as
.B %
followed by that character.

.SH RETURN VALUE
On success,
.B _printf()
returns the number of characters printed (excluding the terminating null byte).
If
.I format
is NULL, or if the format string ends with a single
.B %
(with no specifier), it returns
.BR -1 .

.SH EXAMPLES
.nf
_printf("Hello %s\\n", "world");
_printf("Value: %d%%\\n", 98);
_printf("%c %i\\n", 'A', -123);
.fi

.SH SEE ALSO
.BR printf (3)

.SH AUTHORS
Written for the Holberton School printf project.
